Multiple Correspondence Analysis

Dataset tea2

This dataset contains 300 individuals and 89 variables.

1. Study of the outliers

The analysis of the graphs does not detect any outlier.

2. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of MCA express 11.13% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 11.13% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This is a very small percentage and the first plane represents a small part of the data variability. This value is greater than the reference value that equals 7.18%, the variability explained by this plane is thus significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 611 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a uniform distribution).

From these observations, it is important to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 2 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the MCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 13 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (46.86% against 38.76%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

Figure 9.2 - Variables factor map (MCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.
